2 Required traceability for a CMP
Every CMP version must link to:

its estimator, HCR, and implementation-system source;
the exact argument set and input-data contract;
the jmMSE commit used for evaluation;
OM and robustness scenario definitions;
performance metric definitions and output artifacts;
review findings and known limitations; and
the decision that changed its status.

3 Normative calculation
Document, in order:

data validation and exclusions;
estimator calculation;
status metric and reference period;
HCR equation and every parameter;
interannual constraints;
rounding and numerical precision;
implementation allocation; and
exceptional-circumstances checks.

1 Paper-08 subset screen
SCW17/Paper-08 documented a reproducible subset test of an empirical index procedure using Chile_CPUE and Offshore_CPUE, cpues.ind with a mean combination, and buffer.hcr. Twelve Latin-hypercube design points varied the limit and lower/upper buffer parameters.
The paper reported that the subset spanned a wide range of Kobe-green performance and that higher green probability could coincide with lower catch over the tuning window. It explicitly cautioned that this subset was not the intended full parameter screen. That qualification is retained here.
Evidence still needed before promotion:

immutable run and design artifacts;
confirmation against the merged jmMSE implementation;
evaluation across the agreed reference and robustness OMs;
the complete agreed performance-metric set;
convergence, failure, and reproducibility diagnostics; and
a recorded working-group interpretation of trade-offs.

2 Paper-09 hockeystick test set
SCW17/Paper-09 converted workshop proposals into a structured set of index-based hockeystick tests. It established several useful implementation controls:

use exact jmMSE index names;
define candidate rows in one table rather than hand-editing controls;
stop when required indices are unavailable rather than substituting silently;
distinguish mean-index tests from loess smoothing sensitivities; and
retain unavailable tests as unavailable until their methods exist.

Those rows seed the CMP registry. Their status remains “test candidate” because Paper-09 described how to run them, not a decision to adopt them.
